Until you get that authoratative indication back as to MX records
you don't know if you're doing the *right* thing or not by going
ahead and trying the direct delivery to the IP addr listed in
the A record.

That machine may, for instance, be some workstation whose SMTP
daemon was left unconfigured.  Or for some other reason connecting
to the SMTP socket and attempting to deliver mail may do the
Wrong Thing, and the administrator may have put out MX records
which tell you the Right Thing to do.

IMHO it'd be better to wait until the records are available .. usually
unavailability of the required nameserver lasts only a short time.
-- 
